\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Quasipotential $V(\lambda ) = s(1) - s(\lambda )$ on coherence space for $N = 1, 5, 10, 20$ environment fragments (EGY parameterization). $V(\lambda )$ is maximum at $\lambda =0$ (unstable coherent frame) and zero at $\lambda =1$ (pointer-state minimum, einselected basis). The basin sharpens and deepens as $N$ increases: each additional environment fragment independently constrains the preferred coherence frame, geometrically narrowing the $V$-minimum---the geometric signature of Quantum Darwinism. The shaded region marks the classical frame attractor ($\lambda > 0.75$).}}{14}{figure.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:quasipotential}{{5}{14}{Quasipotential $V(\lambda ) = s(1) - s(\lambda )$ on coherence space for $N = 1, 5, 10, 20$ environment fragments (EGY parameterization). $V(\lambda )$ is maximum at $\lambda =0$ (unstable coherent frame) and zero at $\lambda =1$ (pointer-state minimum, einselected basis). The basin sharpens and deepens as $N$ increases: each additional environment fragment independently constrains the preferred coherence frame, geometrically narrowing the $V$-minimum---the geometric signature of Quantum Darwinism. The shaded region marks the classical frame attractor ($\lambda > 0.75$)}{figure.5}{}}
